&quot;There is only one basic human right, the right to do as you damn well please. And with it comes the only basic human duty, the duty to take the consequences.&quot; 
... attributed to PJ O'Rourke 

I don't know much about the guy (except for a glance at the Wiki entry), but I think that quote is fun.

To quote a guy I know ...   

&quot;  
Prop 8 - Where I stand  
Friday, November 7, 2008 at 12:13am  
I'm sad. It kills me that the people of California discriminated based on semantics. It's convenient to hide behind &quot;marriage is between a man and a woman&quot; but ultimately you've just made the lives of people that work with you, live next to you, and call you friend a little bit harder. Love thy neighbor is not conditional and it shouldn't be convenient. I took a moment to review &quot;marriage&quot; and &quot;civil union&quot; and they are not the same. I see &quot;Yes on 8&quot; as a blight on the soul of this nation. I don't need explanations and I'm not asking for a discussion. 
&quot;

"How can he remember well his ignorance - which his growth requires - who has so often to use his knowledge?"&nbsp; 

Welcome to a rousing game of Attribute That Quote!&nbsp; 

In many cases I wouldn't agree with the guy's point. In some I do.&nbsp; 

--------------------------------------------------------------------------&nbsp; 

I agreed to be the shop steward for my office. That's eleven people. Some have the idea that since NO ONE ELSE IN CALIFORNIA wants that job, I am logically the shop steward for all of California as well. We'll see about that one.&nbsp; 

-------------------------------------------------------------------------- 

"So, are you guys 'official' yet?"&nbsp; 
"Well, umm, I dunno, not really..."&nbsp; 
"Do you have an anniversary?"&nbsp; 
"Yeah." 
"Well that makes you 'official'."&nbsp; 
.... 
... 
.. 

Damn. Noone told me that. Who the hell made up these rules, anyway?
